WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.840 --> 00:00:02.770
Is global warming a hoax?

00:00:02.770 --> 00:00:04.661
What if the Earth&nbsp;is actually getting cooler?

00:00:04.661 --> 00:00:07.658
The climate has always been changing,
so what’s the big deal?

00:00:07.658 --> 00:00:10.726
Myths and disinformation about 
climate change are all around us.

00:00:10.726 --> 00:00:14.671
But while it can be a&nbsp;controversial and 
politically charged topic in some parts of the world,

00:00:14.671 --> 00:00:16.777
the climate crisis is&nbsp;
not a matter of opinion,

00:00:16.777 --> 00:00:19.132
or about which political party you support.

00:00:19.132 --> 00:00:22.140
It’s rooted in hard evidence&nbsp;that scientists 
have been collecting for decades.

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:27.692
So today, we’re going to debunk 10 of the 
most&nbsp;common climate change myths.

00:00:27.692 --> 00:00:29.191
Let’s dive right in.

00:00:29.191 --> 00:00:32.801
Myth number 1: global warming stopped in 1998.

00:00:32.801 --> 00:00:36.179
Here’s a chart showing average global&nbsp;
temperatures since the year 1880,

00:00:36.179 --> 00:00:40.893
which clearly shows that the Earth has&nbsp;
gotten warmer, especially since the 1920s.

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:49.269
Here’s another view of the same data, 
but this&nbsp;time stretching back to 1850,

00:00:49.269 --> 00:00:52.082
which again shows a warming trend 
over the last 100 years.

00:00:52.082 --> 00:00:55.462
But wait a minute. What if we zoom in 
to take a closer look at the data,

00:00:55.462 --> 00:00:58.371
let’s&nbsp;say, for the period between 1998 and 2012?

00:00:58.371 --> 00:01:03.139
If we only look at that period, the&nbsp;Earth 
hasn’t gotten any warmer since 1998!

00:01:03.139 --> 00:01:05.396
Well, first of all, that’s cherry picking.

00:01:05.396 --> 00:01:09.496
But&nbsp;it is true that the Earth did warm more slowly 
during the period from 1998 to 2012

00:01:09.496 --> 00:01:12.000
than it did in&nbsp;the 20 to 30 years prior.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.503
And yes, global warming slowed down, 
but it certainly didn’t stop.

00:01:16.503 --> 00:01:19.058
Climate scientists call it 
a “global warming hiatus”,

00:01:19.058 --> 00:01:23.740
and it was mainly caused by a natural&nbsp;cycle in the 
Pacific Ocean called El Niño–Southern Oscillation.

00:01:23.740 --> 00:01:27.651
There was also a decrease in energy&nbsp;
from the sun, which we’ll talk about later.

00:01:27.651 --> 00:01:31.244
The reason it’s called a hiatus is that 
the&nbsp;slowdown was only temporary,

00:01:31.244 --> 00:01:35.267
and since 2012, the planet has 
continued to warm faster than ever.

00:01:35.267 --> 00:01:42.202
In fact, each of the last nine years, from 2013 to 2021, 
rank among the 10 hottest years on record

00:01:42.202 --> 00:01:47.189
– not to mention that the period from 2011 to 
2020 was the hottest decade ever recorded.

00:01:47.189 --> 00:01:50.000
So no, global warming didn’t stop in the 90s.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.301
In fact, every single year since&nbsp;2013 
has been even hotter than 1998.

00:01:55.301 --> 00:01:59.826
Myth number 2: Global warming has stopped, 
and&nbsp;the world is getting cooler. 

00:01:59.826 --> 00:02:02.521
And chances are, it’s cold 
where you are right now!

00:02:02.521 --> 00:02:05.101
So, let’s just ignore all of the signs 
that the Earth is getting hotter, 

00:02:05.101 --> 00:02:07.586
from&nbsp;rising air, land and sea 
temperatures to rising sea levels

00:02:07.586 --> 00:02:10.166
to melting glaciers to spring&nbsp;arriving earlier…

00:02:10.166 --> 00:02:12.792
and let’s focus instead on the fact 
that it gets cold sometimes!

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:15.889
There’s a big difference 
between weather&nbsp;and climate.

00:02:15.889 --> 00:02:21.252
Weather is what it’s like right now&nbsp;– whether
it’s hot or cold, sunny or cloudy, rainy or dry.

00:02:21.252 --> 00:02:26.290
Climate is about long-term averages: it's about how the 
weather usually is at a given place and time. 

00:02:26.290 --> 00:02:30.542
And the reason we call it “climate change”&nbsp;and not 
“weather change” is that the Earth as a&nbsp;whole

00:02:30.542 --> 00:02:34.560
is getting hotter over a span of decades&nbsp;
– not necessarily everywhere and every day.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:39.069
So, there will still be cold days even though&nbsp;
the Earth is getting hotter overall.

00:02:39.069 --> 00:02:41.495
In fact,&nbsp;we’re probably going to see even
more extreme&nbsp;weather

00:02:41.495 --> 00:02:43.468
not just in summer but also in&nbsp;winter.

00:02:43.468 --> 00:02:47.305
As the Arctic gets hotter,&nbsp;
it’s destabilizing the polar vortex,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:47.305 --> 00:02:50.325
bringing freezing temperatures to&nbsp;
places that don’t normally see snow,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:50.325 --> 00:02:54.360
like Texas and northern Mexico. In other&nbsp;
words: global warming can be cold, too.

00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:58.650
But wait a minute: how do we know that it’s&nbsp;
going to continue to get warmer? 

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:02.994
Scientists&nbsp;rely on models 
to predict climate change.

00:03:02.994 --> 00:03:05.508
Myth number 3 is that 
those models aren’t reliable,

00:03:05.508 --> 00:03:09.418
and that scientists wrongly&nbsp;predicted 
an ice age back in the 1970s.&nbsp;

00:03:09.418 --> 00:03:13.860
Models are mathematical representations
of reality&nbsp;that can be used to estimate general trends.

00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:16.372
Climate modeling is a lot like weather&nbsp;
forecasting:

00:03:16.372 --> 00:03:20.868
it makes predictions based&nbsp;on things like wind patterns, 
ocean currents,&nbsp;and changes in temperature,

00:03:20.868 --> 00:03:23.991
only that these&nbsp;predictions take place 
over a much longer span&nbsp;of time,

00:03:23.991 --> 00:03:26.222
usually decades or even centuries.

00:03:26.222 --> 00:03:30.660
We can already tell how accurate 
a climate model&nbsp;is by hindcasting,

00:03:30.660 --> 00:03:33.077
which means running it using&nbsp;data from 
the past to see how well it can predict

00:03:33.077 --> 00:03:35.400
events and trends that have already happened.

00:03:35.400 --> 00:03:39.879
It turns out the models used by the&nbsp;
Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC)

00:03:39.879 --> 00:03:43.200
have been pretty accurate at&nbsp;predicting 
temperature changes since 1970,

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:47.678
which they managed to hindcast
to within&nbsp;8%–17%.

00:03:47.678 --> 00:03:54.240
And in this recent study,&nbsp;14 out of 17 models managed 
to accurately&nbsp;predict global warming between 1970 and 2007.&nbsp;

00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:56.573
But back to the whole ice age saga:

00:03:56.573 --> 00:04:01.362
Back in the&nbsp;late 1960s and 70s, only a few studies
predicted that the Earth would get cooler.

00:04:01.362 --> 00:04:05.233
The vast majority&nbsp;quite rightly 
thought it would get warmer.

00:04:05.233 --> 00:04:09.180
Myth number 4: Antarctica is&nbsp;
gaining ice rather than losing it.

00:04:09.180 --> 00:04:13.200
Most scientists agree that the eastern part 
of&nbsp;Antarctica is gaining mass in the form of either

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:17.117
ice, snowfall, or both. That’s because 
as the&nbsp;continent gets warmer,

00:04:17.117 --> 00:04:20.205
it’s becoming more humid, 
leading to increased snowfall.

00:04:20.205 --> 00:04:23.858
West Antarctica, on&nbsp;the other hand,
is losing mass faster than ever

00:04:23.858 --> 00:04:28.260
as global warming causes its glaciers to melt,&nbsp;
which is contributing to rising sea levels.

00:04:28.260 --> 00:04:33.540
But back in 2015, NASA published a study that&nbsp;
contradicted every other study up to that point.

00:04:33.540 --> 00:04:38.880
It found that Antarctica is gaining ice overall&nbsp;
because snowfall in East Antarctica is increasing

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:41.734
more quickly than glaciers in 
West Antarctica are&nbsp;melting.

00:04:41.734 --> 00:04:45.935
The study concluded that Antarctica was 
not contributing to rising sea levels as a result.

00:04:45.935 --> 00:04:49.337
The NASA study was instantly picked up by
conservative news outlets like Fox News

00:04:49.337 --> 00:04:51.935
and&nbsp;Breitbart as proof that 
global warming wasn’t&nbsp;real.

00:04:51.935 --> 00:04:55.260
But other scientists quickly pointed&nbsp;out
some issues with the study’s methodology,

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:59.040
and many more recent studies have found&nbsp;
that the NASA study probably overestimated

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:01.789
how quickly East Antarctica is gaining mass.

00:05:01.789 --> 00:05:06.144
Today, the scientific consensus is that 
Antarctica is still losing ice overall,

00:05:06.144 --> 00:05:08.700
and the NASA&nbsp;study is the only one 
that suggests otherwise.

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:12.012
That brings us onto myth number 5: 

00:05:12.690 --> 00:05:17.188
scientists&nbsp;aren’t really sure if climate change is real,&nbsp;
and there’s no scientific consensus.

00:05:17.188 --> 00:05:20.610
But multiple studies have shown that 
at least 90%&nbsp;of climate scientists agree 

00:05:20.610 --> 00:05:23.940
that climate change is&nbsp;not only real 
but also primarily caused by humans.

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:28.380
There have been four studies that find that&nbsp;
97% of publishing climatologists agree with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:35.681
that statement, while other studies put&nbsp;
that figure at 91%, 93%, 99%, or even 100%.

00:05:35.681 --> 00:05:38.940
What’s interesting about these studies is that&nbsp;
they found that the more qualified an expert is,

00:05:38.940 --> 00:05:42.336
the more likely they are to 
agree with the&nbsp;consensus.

00:05:42.336 --> 00:05:48.215
Climatologists who publish regularly in&nbsp;peer-reviewed journals 
are the most likely to say&nbsp;that climate change is mainly caused by humans,&nbsp;

00:05:48.244 --> 00:05:54.390
while among non-publishing climatologists,
that&nbsp;consensus drops to 66%–87%.&nbsp;

00:05:54.390 --> 00:05:57.943
And let’s not forget the crown&nbsp;
jewel of climate science, the IPCC,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.943 --> 00:06:00.026
which brings together hundreds of leading experts

00:06:00.026 --> 00:06:02.462
to produce the definitive assessments 
on climate&nbsp;change.

00:06:02.462 --> 00:06:06.068
According to its latest report,&nbsp;not only are 
humans causing climate change,

00:06:06.068 --> 00:06:09.000
but we’re already suffering the effects&nbsp;
of more frequent disasters like droughts,

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.197
heatwaves and floods, which are only going&nbsp;
to get worse if we don’t act quickly.

00:06:13.197 --> 00:06:16.790
Myth number 6: so, we’ve established&nbsp;
that global warming is real.

00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:19.399
But what&nbsp;if it’s just some sort of natural phenomenon?

00:06:19.399 --> 00:06:22.799
Well, here’s the Earth’s atmosphere, which 
keeps&nbsp;us warm by trapping heat from the sun 

00:06:22.799 --> 00:06:26.134
using gases&nbsp;like carbon dioxide, 
methane and ozone,

00:06:26.134 --> 00:06:28.474
which are&nbsp;collectively known 
as greenhouse gases,

00:06:28.474 --> 00:06:31.172
and their&nbsp;warming effect is known as the greenhouse effect.

00:06:31.172 --> 00:06:35.940
If the Earth didn’t have an atmosphere, it&nbsp;
would be around 33°C colder than it really is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:38.751
making it almost totally uninhabitable for humans.

00:06:39.410 --> 00:06:43.875
Temperature and carbon dioxide in the atmosphere 
have been closely linked throughout the Earth’s&nbsp;history.

00:06:43.875 --> 00:06:48.031
During the Eocene, which was between&nbsp;
56 million and 34 million years ago, 

00:06:48.031 --> 00:06:51.303
carbon&nbsp;dioxide levels were almost 
four times higher&nbsp;than they are today, 

00:06:51.303 --> 00:06:56.196
at around 1,500 parts per&nbsp;million, which is why 
temperatures were about 10°C hotter.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.196 --> 00:07:00.660
During the last ice age, on the&nbsp;other hand,
they were between 180 and 300 ppm.&nbsp;

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:05.880
But here’s where we come in: each year, humans&nbsp;
are emitting about 9.5 billion metric tons of

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:08.874
carbon dioxide into the atmosphere 
by burning&nbsp;fossil fuels,

00:07:08.874 --> 00:07:12.340
plus an additional 1.5 billion tons 
through deforestation.

00:07:12.340 --> 00:07:18.201
Today,&nbsp;carbon dioxide levels are the highest&nbsp;
they’ve been in 800,000 years, at 420 ppm.

00:07:18.201 --> 00:07:22.301
That’s why the Earth has gotten about
1.2°C&nbsp;hotter since the late 19th century.

00:07:22.301 --> 00:07:24.840
It’s almost&nbsp;double the warming
at the end of the last ice age,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:30.000
and it’s happening at least 100 times&nbsp;
faster. The only reason for that is us.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.353
That is, unless you believe myth number 7:

00:07:32.353 --> 00:07:35.280
the sun&nbsp;is burning brighter 
and making the Earth hotter.

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:38.888
The sun’s energy has actually been&nbsp;
decreasing since the 1980s,

00:07:38.888 --> 00:07:42.000
and yet&nbsp;the Earth is still getting hotter.
If the sun were getting brighter,

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.660
we would see that reflected across&nbsp;
the entire atmosphere. But instead,

00:07:45.660 --> 00:07:49.740
only the lower atmosphere is getting warmer&nbsp;
while the upper atmosphere is getting cooler,

00:07:49.740 --> 00:07:53.072
and that’s because more and more heat is&nbsp;
being trapped in the lower atmosphere

00:07:53.100 --> 00:07:55.008
by&nbsp;the greenhouse gases that we’re emitting.

00:07:55.008 --> 00:07:59.601
But in any case, solar fluctuations only&nbsp;have a 
very minor impact on the Earth’s&nbsp;temperature

00:07:59.601 --> 00:08:02.438
– in the range of about&nbsp;0.1°C at most.

00:08:02.438 --> 00:08:05.400
So, there’s no way it could&nbsp;have caused 
the 1.2°C of warming so far.

00:08:06.370 --> 00:08:10.269
So, remember how I said that the Earth used 
to be&nbsp;10°C hotter back in the Eocene?

00:08:12.682 --> 00:08:15.409
Myth number 8: the climate is&nbsp;
constantly changing,

00:08:15.409 --> 00:08:18.904
and it has been warmer&nbsp;in the past, 
so it’s no big deal, right?

00:08:18.904 --> 00:08:23.550
There are natural cycles that cause the Earth’s&nbsp;climate 
to fluctuate between cooler and warmer&nbsp;periods. 

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:28.433
For instance, the El Niño–Southern&nbsp;Oscillation (ENSO)
is a climate pattern in the Pacific Ocean 

00:08:28.433 --> 00:08:31.980
consisting of a warm phase&nbsp;
called El Niño and a cool phase called La Niña,

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:36.134
and it swings back and forth between the&nbsp;
two phases every 3–7 years.

00:08:36.134 --> 00:08:39.840
And the Earth also fluctuates between&nbsp;
cold periods, otherwise known as ice ages,

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:44.615
and warmer periods, known as interglacials,&nbsp;
roughly every 100,000 years

00:08:44.615 --> 00:08:49.324
due to what are known as Milankovitch cycles, 
which are&nbsp;fluctuations in the Earth’s orbit and tilt.

00:08:49.324 --> 00:08:53.328
But the warming that we’re seeing today
isn’t&nbsp;part of any of these natural cycles.

00:08:53.328 --> 00:08:58.762
The Earth hasn’t been this hot in at least
12,000&nbsp;years – and perhaps even 125,000 years.

00:08:58.762 --> 00:09:03.960
And on that note, here’s myth number 9:
the&nbsp;benefits from climate change outweigh the costs.

00:09:03.960 --> 00:09:07.770
It’s true that a few regions of the world&nbsp;
could experience benefits from climate change.

00:09:07.770 --> 00:09:10.808
Canada and Russia, for instance,&nbsp;
could gain huge areas of farmland

00:09:10.808 --> 00:09:15.101
that are&nbsp;currently too cold for farming, as well&nbsp;as 
new shipping routes across the Arctic&nbsp;Ocean.

00:09:15.101 --> 00:09:18.000
But even those countries are already&nbsp;
suffering from melting permafrost

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:22.020
and raging&nbsp;wildfires in the Arctic, which is warming&nbsp;
twice as quickly as the rest of the Earth. 

00:09:22.680 --> 00:09:26.491
And for everyone else, there aren’t really&nbsp;
any benefits from climate change.

00:09:26.491 --> 00:09:32.340
According&nbsp;to the latest IPCC report, over 40% of 
the world’s&nbsp;population is “highly vulnerable”,

00:09:32.340 --> 00:09:35.580
and by that, they mean half the world currently suffers&nbsp;
from water shortages at some point every year,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:38.542
one in three people are exposed 
to deadly heat&nbsp;stress,

00:09:38.542 --> 00:09:41.611
a billion people could be affected 
by&nbsp;rising sea levels by 2050,

00:09:41.611 --> 00:09:47.004
and an extra 180&nbsp;million people will go hungry by 2050 
due to&nbsp;crop failure caused by extreme weather.

00:09:47.004 --> 00:09:50.000
So, the climate has changed before,&nbsp;
but humans have never experienced

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.920
this much&nbsp;warming this quickly, 
and it’s going to be rough.

00:09:53.307 --> 00:09:55.426
And lastly, myth number 10:

00:09:55.426 --> 00:09:58.134
climate change solutions are&nbsp;too expensive 
and would hurt the economy.

00:10:04.075 --> 00:10:10.157
According to this study, the world could lose up to 
18% of its GDP&nbsp;by 2050 if we do nothing,

00:10:10.157 --> 00:10:13.932
and 11% even if we&nbsp;manage to keep 
global warming to 2°C.

00:10:13.932 --> 00:10:19.686
And by 2100, climate change could cost 37%&nbsp;
of global GDP, based on this study.

00:10:19.686 --> 00:10:22.195
But we don’t even have to look 
that&nbsp;far into the future.

00:10:22.195 --> 00:10:25.708
In just the next five&nbsp;years, 
companies will lose US$1.2 trillion

00:10:25.708 --> 00:10:28.281
to supply chain disruption from climate change.

00:10:28.281 --> 00:10:31.727
On the other hand, it could cost 
less than 1% of&nbsp;global GDP

00:10:31.727 --> 00:10:35.000
to mitigate climate change by 2030&nbsp;
using cost-effective solutions

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:38.643
like improving&nbsp;energy efficiency, 
expanding renewable energy,

00:10:38.643 --> 00:10:41.261
and restoring forests and degraded landscapes.

00:10:41.261 --> 00:10:45.480
So, there you have it: next time you hear someone&nbsp;
repeating any of these myths, you know the drill:

00:10:45.480 --> 00:10:49.200
send them this video. And if you like what&nbsp;
you saw, don’t forget to drop us a like,

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:52.860
leave us a comment, and hit that subscribe&nbsp;
button for more episodes of Landscape TV.&nbsp;

00:10:52.860 --> 00:10:55.260
Thanks for watching, and&nbsp;
we’ll see you on the next one.

